{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522400"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:44:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:44:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13826"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13826"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.55,0.04,0.14,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6443"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107503"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6443"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13826"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89983"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"819"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"2310"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12725"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12726"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30519"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39893"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107503"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a three-week history of an itchy, circular rash on his back. He noticed it during his holiday surfing in Bali, and thinks it spread since then. He is otherwise well. He has a medical history of gastroesophageal reflux and eczema. His only regular medications are esomeprazole and hydrocortisone cream, which he mainly requires during the winter months for eczema flares. He has allergies to pet dander.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a large erythematous, scaly patch with raised borders on his back only, measuring about 10 cm in diameter (Image). The rest of the skin examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral fluconazole","Topical terbinafine","Oral prednisilone","Topical hydrocortisone","Topical calcipotriol"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with tinea corporis, also known as ringworm of the body. The characteristic features include circular, erythematous, scaly patches with raised borders. For localised tinea corporis, the most appropriate first-line treatment is a \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical terbinifine\u003C/strong\u003E cream, applied twice daily for two to four weeks. Topical antifungal agents are generally effective and have fewer side effects compared to systemic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral fluconazole\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective systemic antifungal agent, but it is usually reserved for extensive, severe, recurrent or topical treatment resistant tinea corporis infections. It is not typically used as first-line therapy for localised disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be used in moderate or severe allergies with the patient\u0027s history of pet dander allergy, however the timeline of weeks does not suit and the rash would be more widespread and hive-like.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for treating tinea corporis. Corticosteroids can worsen fungal infections and potentially lead to a condition called tinea incognito, where the typical appearance of the rash is masked, making diagnosis more difficult. Seabather\u0027s eruption may be another differential given the timing with his time in the ocean, and this could be managed with 1% hydrocortisone cream if persisting. However, this would present with multiple small red papules, pustules or urticarial welts rather than the clearly demarcated rash as above. Similarly, granuloma annulare can also present with ring-like lesions and would respond to high dose corticosteroid cream. However it would less likely to have so many lesions and spreading as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical calcipotriol\u003C/strong\u003E is a treatment used for psoriasis and is not appropriate for treating tinea corporis. Whilst psoriasis can present as patches of red skin, it typically has silvery scales and dry in appearance. Calcipotriol is a vitamin D analogue that helps to regulate skin cell production and reduce inflammation in psoriasis but has no antifungal properties.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Topical antifungal agents are first-line treatment for localised tinea corporis in immunocompetent patients."],"references":["Bell H. Tinea corporis In: Dermnet NZ [online]. 2020. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/tinea-corporis","Leung L. Ring-like lesions on the hand: A Case study. Australian Family Practice. 2012:41 (1). Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/january-february/ring-like-lesions-on-the-hand"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89983"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13826"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20773"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20773"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://a